IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde once said she is open to serving another five years as the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Managing Director.
She should stay on.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she herself started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, taking over an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath damaged the reputation of multilateral lending institutions led by the West and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's reputation.
Many looked to her personal qualities — which is only appropriate.
She is candid, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate settings) consistently said she was willing to speak difficult truths while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms of agreements rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they must build firewalls to prevent financial contagion. It was harsh advice, but Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she loudly urged support from the IMF to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
During this process, she gave the institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a human face.
For example, helping manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to allow the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist people displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over a million people reside in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak erupted in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to provide debt relief to affected countries, allowing them to improve the treatment of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF had used its own capital in such a manner.
Additionally, Lagarde recognized that the world today faces three of the most important challenges, and she took action on them.
First, she strongly demanded that more women be brought into the workforce, and she herself is an exemplar of the value of women in leadership positions.
In various countries, from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urged leaders to stop wasting such a vast human resource — and thus realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a matter of basic fairness.
The IMF's research highlights a direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to demonstrate this, but its position has made the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde has personally advocated for this, which has been key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played a significant role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will have alarming disruptive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase manufacturing efficiency and reduce costs, but it also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be less than before.
This emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences are worth our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics will say it is time for a developing country representative to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's possession of such privilege is already difficult to justify in today's world.
Some will also say that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded significant results, proving that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some will also point out that she faces accusations related to financial scandals in France, which could distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn was embroiled in a scandal, critics argued that the IMF must never again be distracted by such incidents.
We will examine these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
The purpose of ending this Western privilege is to make the leadership selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice for IMF Managing Director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not jointly nominated an alternative.
Having an European serve as IMF Managing Director may also have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision last year to include the RMB in the currency basket that determines the value of its Special Drawing Rights.
Additionally, Lagarde demonstrated impressive political flexibility, ultimately persuading both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms. These reforms not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
Last year, Lagarde made some personally styled, and some would say inappropriate, comments on the Greece issue.
But she is not the culprit who brought economic pain to the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF has fully demonstrated that no IMF Managing Director in history has done as much as she has to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of people during crises.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde in France were opposed by the French prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to making the IMF adapt to the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to complete her work.
